7.3 RAG Pipeline Flow
Pipeline: Document Upload/Detection → Text Extraction → Cleaning & Chunking (512 tokens, 64-token overlap) → Embedding Generation (local model) → Chroma/Qdrant Upsert → [Query Time] Semantic Search (Top-K=8) → Re-ranking → Context Assembly → Ollama/Gemini/Groq LLM Generation with Citations → Response Streaming

7.4 Security Implementation — Phased Approach
Security is implemented in three phases tied to product maturity. Front-loading all security work before MVP wastes engineering effort; delaying foundational items creates irreversible architectural debt. The split below is deliberate.

Phase 1 — Build These on Day 1 (near-zero extra effort)
Do Now: These items cost less than 1 day total to implement and are nearly impossible to retrofit cleanly later. Build them in from the start.

Item	How to Implement	Why Now
HTTPS / TLS everywhere	Automatic on Vercel, Railway, and Render — zero config	Retroactively enforcing HTTPS breaks existing integrations
Never log document content	Set log level to exclude request bodies at FastAPI startup	Near impossible to audit and purge logs retroactively
Secrets in environment variables	Use Railway/Render built-in env vars; never hardcode in source	A leaked API key in git history is permanent
Supabase Row-Level Security (RLS)	One SQL policy per table: users can only read their own rows	Applying RLS to a populated database causes downtime
Basic auth (Supabase Auth / NextAuth)	You need login anyway — build it correctly first time	Retrofitting auth means rewriting every API endpoint
Input length limits on API endpoints	FastAPI request body size limit (e.g., 50MB max) + timeout	Prevents accidental or malicious resource exhaustion

Phase 2 — Add After MVP (when you have real users)
Post-MVP: Implement these once you have validated product-market fit and have real users whose data needs protecting. Estimated: 1–2 week sprint.

Item	Tool / Approach
Encryption at rest for document chunks	Supabase built-in encryption or application-level AES-256 via Python cryptography library (free)
API rate limiting	slowapi (FastAPI middleware, free OSS) — prevent abuse of your free LLM tier quota
Prompt injection defense	Strip/escape user inputs before LLM injection; add a content moderation prefix in the system prompt
Document auto-deletion policy	Scheduled Supabase Edge Function to delete vectors + files older than N days (free)
CORS policy hardening	Restrict origins to your extension ID and web app domain only
Dependency vulnerability scanning	GitHub Dependabot (free) — enable in repo settings, takes 2 minutes

Phase 3 — Enterprise-Only (when selling to large organisations)
Enterprise-Only: Only build these when you have paying enterprise customers who explicitly require them. Building them earlier is waste.

Item	Tool / Approach
SSO / SAML 2.0 / OIDC	Supabase Pro + Auth0 or WorkOS (paid) — only needed for org-level login
Audit logs (who read what, when)	Append-only Postgres table with user_id, document_id, action, timestamp — simple to build, needed for compliance
SOC 2 Type II audit	Engage a third-party auditor — only relevant once enterprise contracts require it
Data residency controls	Deploy Qdrant + Supabase in the required region (EU, US, India) — infra config, not code change
On-premises / air-gapped deployment	Docker Compose bundle of all services — offer as Enterprise add-on
GDPR / DPDP Act formal compliance	Privacy policy + DPA templates + data deletion API endpoint — legal effort, not engineering

